                     <interp inst="def1-974-18450407" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-974-18450407" type="surname" value="LIMB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-974-18450407" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SARAH LIMB</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18450407-974-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18450407-974-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18450407-974-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>for stealing 12 sovereigns, 12 half-sovereigns, 1 crown, 16 half-crowns, 11 shillings, 8 sixpences, And 3 groats, the monies of <persName id="t18450407-name-1052" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1052" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1052" type="surname" value="NUNN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1052" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18450407-974-offence-1 t18450407-name-1052"></join>James Nunn</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The prosecutor being deaf and dumb gave his evidence by signs, which were interpreted.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1053" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1053" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1053" type="surname" value="NUNN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1053" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES NUNN</persName>
                  </hi>. I lodged and slept in a back room up stairs at the prisoner's house—no one slept in the room but me—on the morning of the 4th of April, I went out at six o'clock—I left a box locked up in my room, in which was 18<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in gold, And 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in silver—there were sovereigns, half-sovereigns, a crown, some half-crowns, shillings, and other silver, and some clothes—I know the money was all right the night before, and the box was locked—I locked it every night and morning—I returned home at seven o'clock in the evening—I could see that my box had been broken open, and the things inside had been all upset—I made the prisoner under<lb></lb>stand</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184504070190"></xptr>
               <p>by writing on a slate that my box had been broken open, and the money was all gone—she went up stairs with me, and I showed her my box—she had never seen the money in my box in my presence, but her daughter had—I made signs to the prisoner that I would get a policeman—my money had been in a bag—this is the bag it was in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had you been lodging with the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two years and a half or three years—she was a well-conducted woman—her furniture was seized that day—I did not owe her any rent—I cannot tell how much there was in my bag when I received it back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1054" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1054" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1054" type="surname" value="WOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1054" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY WOOD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable K</hi> 44.) On the evening of the 4th of April the prosecutor came to me at Poplar station—he showed me his shirt, which was torn—there was another person with him—I went to the prisoner's house in Grundy-street—I found the door partly open, and the prisoner was in the passage—she went iuto a back room—I followed her—she took hold of the prosecutor, and said, "<hi rend="italic">Jem</hi>, don't give me in charge, I took your money, and will pay you back again"—she put this bag into his hand, containing six half-sovereigns, one crown, and some other silver—I went up stairs, and found the box with the mark of a chisel near the lock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What was the amount of the money in the bag? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she gave me a little silver at the station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1055" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1055" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1055" type="surname" value="DAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1055" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES DAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a broker. I went to the prisoner's house to levy for arrears of rent on the 4th of April—the amount was 14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she said she could not pay me—I said I was sorry to come to see her again, as I had distrained on her fourteen months before—I proceeded to take the inventory—she said she would get the money—she brought 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in sove<lb></lb>reigns and half-sovereigns—she got change, and paid me.</p>
